Source: Xinhua News Agency online, Mon 11 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-04/11/content_2813059.htm>

Angola: Marburg hemorrhagic fever death toll approaches 200
-----------------------------------------------
The death toll in Angola from the world's deadliest outbreak of
Marburg virus infection, with 9 more deaths, is approaching the 200
mark. The UN World Health Organization stated that, as of Sun 10 Apr
2005, the total number of cases nationwide is 218, that 193 people
have died, and added that 360 others were under surveillance in the
southern African country, where the outbreak was 1st detected in
October 2005. The death toll, based on figures compiled up to Friday
[8 Apr 2005] was 184.
Marburg virus, whose exact origin is unknown, spreads through contact
with bodily fluids, such as blood, excrement, vomit, saliva, sweat
and tears, but can be contained with relatively simple health
precautions. The outbreak in Angola has overtaken an earlier outbreak
in the Democratic Republic of Congo as the largest ever recorded of
the virus, 1st detected in 1967 when German laboratory workers in the
town of Marburg were infected by monkeys from Uganda.
