Date: Mon 11 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Channel News Asia online, Agence France Presse report, Mon 11
Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/health/view/141978/1/.html>

Angola: health teams race to track new Marburg cases
-----------------------------------------------
Epidemiologists in the northern Angolan town of Uige are working
overtime to trace new cases of the deadly Marburg virus, which has
claimed nearly 200 lives and sparked panic in the war-devastated
southern African nation. Every morning, teams from the World Health
Organization comb the town, devastated by a 27-year civil war, to try
and pinpoint new cases of the hemorrhagic fever, which has so far
infected 218 people and killed 193 in the world's worst outbreak.
"We visit our contacts and look for suspected cases," Francois
Libama, a WHO epidemiologist told Agence France Presse (AFP), as
4x4's set out to scan the derelict town, which still bears the scars
of the bitter civil war which raged here until 2 years ago. "If we
find a suspected case, we call in the special teams to come and
remove the body," Libama said, as he drove to a home in Kakuia, a few
km from the center of the town, where a suspected case had been
reported.
A few hours later, Libama, who has done similar work during 3
previous outbreaks of Ebola hemorrhagic fever, checked on 2 Marburg
"alerts" at homes where young children had died from causes other
than the feared fever. The team finds another home, where a family
had previously lost a year-and-a-half old child to Marburg a week
ago, empty. "They have left; they have gone back to their village,"
an elderly neighbor said, [adding that] the family's village was more
than 100 km (60 miles) away from Uige through thick jungle. "We have
lost them," Lubama told AFP.
Funeral teams here have been met with fear and anger and also some
superstition. "There is a lot of superstition and witchcraft. For
example, doctor Alexandre Matombo, the Uige hospital director, has
been accused by residents of causing the illness," Lubama told AFP.
Anthropologists meanwhile said the burial teams were being sensitized
to local custom and tradition. They proposed that a ritual washing of
hands after a funeral be replaced by a symbolic washing with
chlorinated water and that burial teams express condolences when they
come to take away a body and allow the family to attend the burial.
"In Africa, we celebrate the death of somebody," said Alain Epelboin,
French anthropologist of the Paris-based National Center for
Scientific Research. "With this epidemic, there is a silence around
the death ... we thought that we need to restore a kind of ritual,"
he told AFP. "When somebody dies, I explain to the neighbors how the
"astronauts" are coming to take the body away," added Julienne Anoko,
another anthropologist, referring to the burial team's full-body
protective "Ebola" suits.
--
