A comment on the control of Marburg hemorrhagic fever
-----------------------------------------------
Medecins san Frontieres (MSF) are quoted in today's New York Times as
saying that the main hospital in Uige, Angola (and perhaps smaller
ones in that region) should be closed in order to combat Marburg
hemorrhagic fever that rages in the country. The thesis is that these
facilities are a principal source of virus transmission. [See part
(1) of ProMED-mail post "Marburg hemorrhagic fever - Angola (22)
20050410.1037" - Mod.CP]
But those who pay no attention to history are certainly doomed to
repeat it! The virtual wipe out of hospital staff during the Ebola
outbreak in Kikwit, Zaire 10 years ago led to ongoing transmission of
disease in homes where family care-givers had absolutely zero
protection against acquisition of disease once a single member became
ill. The MSF team certainly needs massive help in the current crisis,
but one thing is clear from experience: filovirus outbreaks will be
controlled only when the populace under attack has confidence in
primary medical care provided by personnel themselves confident that
they can deal with the disease and themselves survive.
Do not close the hospitals. Retool them urgently.
--
Karl M. Johnson MD
<KarlMJohnson@aol.com>
[Karl Johnson's warning is based on experience and should not be
glossed over without serious consideration. It is possible that the
newswires are misrepresenting the full situation and there are plans
to have independent, free standing isolation units for care of
clinical cases of Marburg in Uige and surrounding areas. The problems
inherent with leaving active cases in their home environment cannot
be overstated. The observation that the hospital(s) has been an
amplifier for transmission is in keeping with prior outbreaks of
viral hemorrhagic fevers in Africa, not unrelated to lack of barrier
protective gear and generalized shortages of gloves, syringes and
needles as mentioned in earlier discussions in this thread. In prior
outbreaks, the implementation of isolation with use of full
protective gear has lead to interruption of transmission.
From the reports coming in from the field, the challenges in front of
the health care sector for interrupting transmission in this outbreak
are great, and remain so for socio-cultural reasons.
We await results of epidemiologic studies of this outbreak. - Mod.MPP]
